<section xml:id="C28.S20">
<title>Definitions and Basic Properties</title>        
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS1">
<title>Modified Mathieu’s Equation</title>        
 
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS1.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C28.S20.SS1.p1.s1">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS1.p1.m1">z</Math> is replaced by <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS1.p1.m2">\pm\mathrm{i}z</Math> , (28.2.1) becomes themodified Mathieu’s equation: <Math equation-number="28.20.1" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E1">w^{\prime\prime}-\left(a-2q\cosh\left(2z\right)\right)w=0,</Math> with its algebraic form <Math equation-number="28.20.2" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E2">{(\zeta^{2}-1)w^{\prime\prime}+\zeta w^{\prime}+\left(4q\zeta^{2}-2q-a\right)w =0}, if \zeta=\cosh z</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS2">
<title>Solutions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.m1">\mathrm{Ce}_{\nu}</Math>, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.m2">\mathrm{Se}_{\nu}</Math>,<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.m3">\mathrm{Me}_{\nu}</Math>, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.m4">\mathrm{Fe}_{n}</Math>, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.m5">\mathrm{Ge}_{n}</Math></title>        
     
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C28.S20.SS2.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="28.20.3" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E3">\mathrm{Ce}_{\nu}\left(z,q\right)=\mathrm{ce}_{\nu}\left(\pm\mathrm{i}z,q \right), if \nu\neq-1,-2,\dots,</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.4" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E4">\mathrm{Se}_{\nu}\left(z,q\right)=\mp\mathrm{i}\mathrm{se}_{\nu}\left(\pm \mathrm{i}z,q\right), if \nu\neq 0,-1,\dots,</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.5" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E5">\mathrm{Me}_{\nu}\left(z,q\right)=\mathrm{me}_{\nu}\left(-\mathrm{i}z,q\right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.6" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E6">\mathrm{Fe}_{n}\left(z,q\right)=\mp\mathrm{i}\mathrm{fe}_{n}\left(\pm\mathrm{i }z,q\right), if n=0,1,\dots,</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.7" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E7">\mathrm{Ge}_{n}\left(z,q\right)=\mathrm{ge}_{n}\left(\pm\mathrm{i}z,q\right), if n=1,2,\dots</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS3">
<title>Solutions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.m1">{\mathrm{M}^{(j)}_{\nu}}</Math></title>        
  
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s1">
Assume first that <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m1">\nu</Math> is real, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m2">q</Math> is positive, and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m3">a=\lambda_{\nu}\left(q\right)</Math> ; see §28.12(i).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s2">
Write <Math equation-number="28.20.8" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E8">h=\sqrt{q}\;(&gt;0)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s3">
Then from §2.7(ii) it is seen that equation (28.20.2) has independent and unique solutions that are asymptotic to <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m5">\zeta^{\ifrac{1}{2}}e^{\pm 2\mathrm{i}h\zeta}</Math> as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m6">\zeta\to\infty</Math> in the respective sectors <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m7">|\operatorname{ph}\left(\mp\mathrm{i}\zeta\right)|\leq\tfrac{3}{2}\pi-\delta</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m8">\delta</Math> being an arbitrary small positive constant.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s4">
It follows that(28.20.1) has independent and unique solutions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m9">{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m10">{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math> such that <Math equation-number="28.20.9" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E9">{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)={H^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(2h\cosh z\right) \left(1+O\left(\operatorname{sech}z\right)\right),</Math> as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m11">\Re z\to+\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m12">-\pi+\delta\leq\Im z\leq 2\pi-\delta</Math> , and <Math equation-number="28.20.10" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E10">{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)={H^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(2h\cosh z\right) \left(1+O\left(\operatorname{sech}z\right)\right),</Math> as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m13">\Re z\to+\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m14">-2\pi+\delta\leq\Im z\leq\pi-\delta</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s5">
See §10.2(ii) for the notation.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="6" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.s6">
In addition, there are unique solutions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m15">{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m16">{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math> that are real when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m17">z</Math> is real and have the properties <Math equation-number="28.20.11" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E11">{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)=J_{\nu}\left(2h\cosh z\right)+e^{|\Im (2h\cosh z)|}O\left(\left(\operatorname{sech}z\right)^{3/2}\right),</Math> <Math equation-number="28.20.12" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E12">{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)=Y_{\nu}\left(2h\cosh z\right)+e^{|\Im (2h\cosh z)|}O\left((\operatorname{sech}z)^{3/2}\right),</Math> as <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m18">\Re z\to+\infty</Math> with <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p1.m19">|\Im z|\leq\pi-\delta</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.s1">
For other values of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.m1">z</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.m2">h</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.m3">\nu</Math> the functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.m4">{\mathrm{M}^{(j)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.m5">j=1,2,3,4</Math> , are determined by analytic continuation.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C28.S20.SS3.p2.s2">
Furthermore, <Math equation-number="28.20.13" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E13">{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)={\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h \right)+\mathrm{i}{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.14" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E14">{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)={\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h \right)-\mathrm{i}{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS4">
<title>Radial Mathieu Functions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS4.m1">{\mathrm{Mc}^{(j)}_{n}}</Math>,<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS4.m2">{\mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{n}}</Math></title>        
     
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS4.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C28.S20.SS4.p1.s1">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS4.p1.m1">j=1,2,3,4</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.15" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E15">{\mathrm{Mc}^{(j)}_{n}}\left(z,h\right)={\mathrm{M}^{(j)}_{n}}\left(z,h\right), if n=0,1,\dots,</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.16" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E16">{\mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{n}}\left(z,h\right)=(-1)^{n}{\mathrm{M}^{(j)}_{-n}}\left(z ,h\right), if n=1,2,\dots</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS5">
<title>Solutions <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.m1">\mathrm{Ie}_{n}</Math>, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.m2">\mathrm{Io}_{n}</Math>,<Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.m3">\mathrm{Ke}_{n}</Math>, <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.m4">\mathrm{Ko}_{n}</Math></title>        
 
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="12" xml:id="C28.S20.SS5.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="28.20.17" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E17">\mathrm{Ie}_{n}\left(z,h\right)={\mathrm{i}^{-n}}{\mathrm{Mc}^{(1)}_{n}}\left( z,\mathrm{i}h\right),</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.18" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E18">\mathrm{Io}_{n}\left(z,h\right)={\mathrm{i}^{-n}}{\mathrm{Ms}^{(1)}_{n}}\left( z,\mathrm{i}h\right),</Math> <Math equation-number="28.20.19" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E19">\mathrm{Ke}_{2m}\left(z,h\right)=(-1)^{m}\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i}{\mathrm{Mc} ^{(3)}_{2m}}\left(z,\mathrm{i}h\right),\mathrm{Ke}_{2m+1}\left(z,h\right)=(-1)^{m+1}\tfrac{1}{2}\pi{\mathrm{Mc}^{(3)} _{2m+1}}\left(z,\mathrm{i}h\right),</Math> <Math equation-number="28.20.20" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E20">\mathrm{Ko}_{2m}\left(z,h\right)=(-1)^{m}\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i}{\mathrm{Ms} ^{(3)}_{2m}}\left(z,\mathrm{i}h\right),\mathrm{Ko}_{2m+1}\left(z,h\right)=(-1)^{m+1}\tfrac{1}{2}\pi{\mathrm{Ms}^{(3)} _{2m+1}}\left(z,\mathrm{i}h\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS6">
<title>Wronskians</title>        
  
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS6.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="13" xml:id="C28.S20.SS6.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="28.20.21" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E21">\mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\right\}=- \mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\right\}={- \mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\right\}= \ifrac{2}{\pi}},\mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\right\}=- \mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\right\}={- \tfrac{1}{2}\mathscr{W}\left\{{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}},{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu} }\right\}=\ifrac{2\mathrm{i}}{\pi}}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
</subsection>
 
<subsection xml:id="C28.S20.SS7">
<title>Shift of Variable</title>        
   
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="14" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p1.s1">
 <Math equation-number="28.20.22" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E22">{\mathrm{M}^{(j)}_{\nu}}\left(z\pm\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)={\mathrm{ M}^{(j)}_{\nu}}\left(z,\pm\mathrm{i}h\right), if \nu\notin\mathbb{Z}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="15" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p2.s1">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p2.m1">n=0,1,2,\dots</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.23" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E23">{\mathrm{Mc}^{(j)}_{2n}}\left(z\pm\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)={\mathrm{ Mc}^{(j)}_{2n}}\left(z,\pm\mathrm{i}h\right),{\mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{2n+1}}\left(z\pm\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)={ \mathrm{Mc}^{(j)}_{2n+1}}\left(z,\pm\mathrm{i}h\right),</Math> <Math equation-number="28.20.24" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E24">{\mathrm{Mc}^{(j)}_{2n+1}}\left(z\pm\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)={ \mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{2n+1}}\left(z,\pm\mathrm{i}h\right),{\mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{2n+2}}\left(z\pm\tfrac{1}{2}\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)={ \mathrm{Ms}^{(j)}_{2n+2}}\left(z,\pm\mathrm{i}h\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="16" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3.s1">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3.m1">s\in\mathbb{Z}</Math> , <Math equation-number="28.20.25" mode="display" xml:id="C28.S20.E25">{\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z+s\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)=e^{\mathrm{i}s\pi\nu}{ \mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right),{\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z+s\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)=e^{-\mathrm{i}s\pi\nu} {\mathrm{M}^{(2)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)+2\mathrm{i}\cot\left(\pi\nu\right) \sin\left(s\pi\nu\right){\mathrm{M}^{(1)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right),{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\left(z+s\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)=-\dfrac{\sin\left({(s- 1)\pi\nu}\right)}{\sin\left(\pi\nu\right)}{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h \right)-e^{-\mathrm{i}\pi\nu}\frac{\sin\left(s\pi\nu\right)}{\sin\left(\pi\nu \right)}{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right),{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z+s\pi\mathrm{i},h\right)=e^{\mathrm{i}\pi\nu} \dfrac{\sin\left(s\pi\nu\right)}{\sin\left(\pi\nu\right)}{\mathrm{M}^{(3)}_{ \nu}}\left(z,h\right)+\frac{\sin\left((s+1)\pi\nu\right)}{\sin\left(\pi\nu \right)}{\mathrm{M}^{(4)}_{\nu}}\left(z,h\right)</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="17" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3.s2">
When <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3.m2">\nu</Math> is an integer the right-hand sides of (28.20.25) are replaced by the their limiting values.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="18" xml:id="C28.S20.SS7.p3.s3">
And for the corresponding identities for the radial functions use (28.20.15) and (28.20.16).
</sentence>

</para>
  
 
</subsection>
 
</section>
